One problem with the accepted answer is that it will also select elements that do not have a <code>foo</code> attribute at all.  Consider:
<code>&lt;div&gt;No foo&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div foo=""&gt;Empty foo&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div foo="x"&gt;XXX&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div foo="y"&gt;YYY&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div foo="z"&gt;ZZZ&lt;/div&gt;
</code>
<code>div:not([foo=''])</code> will select both the first and second <code>div</code> elements.  If you only want <code>div</code> elements that have an attribute foo that is set to an empty string, you should use:
<code>div[foo]:not([foo=''])
</code>
If you want all elements with attribute <code>foo</code> that is neither <code>y</code> nor <code>z</code>, you should use:
<code>div[foo]:not([foo='y']):not([foo='z'])
</code>
<code>:not([foo=''])
{
    background: red;
}
</code>
http://jsfiddle.net/gsLvuys0/
BTW if you are trying to select all elements with a certain attribute except for ones with the specific value, you could do something like this:
<code>[data-foo]:not([data-foo="foo"]) {
  /* matches &lt;div data-foo="bar"&gt; but not &lt;div data-foo="foo"&gt; or &lt;div&gt; */
}
</code>
You can select the first one using 
<code>[foo = 'x']{
  background:red;
}
</code>
FIDDLE
Read this
Use the code like this:
<code>div[foo]:not([foo=''])
{
    /* CSS Applied to divs having foo value Not nothing (or having a foo value assigned) */
}
</code>

