You can also iterate with a simple for:
<code>var files = field.photo.files;

for (var i = 0; i &lt; files.length; i++) {
    console.log(files[i]);
}
</code>
A <code>FileList</code> is not an <code>Array</code>, but it does conform to its contract (has <code>length</code> and numeric indices), so we can "borrow" <code>Array</code> methods:
<code>Array.prototype.forEach.call(field.photo.files, function(file) { ... });
</code>
Since you're obviously using ES6, you could also make it a proper <code>Array</code>, using the new <code>Array.from</code> method:
<code>Array.from(field.photo.files).forEach(file =&gt; { ... });
</code>
In ES6 you can use:
<code>[...field.photo.files].forEach(file =&gt; console.log(file));
</code>
Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax
The lodash library has a _forEach method that loops through all collection entities, such as arrays and objects, including the FileList:
<code>_.forEach(field.photo.files,(file =&gt; {
     // looping code
})
</code>
