Can also do something like this:
<code>&lt;MyJsx objectProps={{
    prop1,
    prop2
}}/&gt;
</code>
This way you don't have to write <code>prop1: prop1</code> (if it is a variable or function such as <code>state</code> <code>setState</code>).
It can then be accessed in the component using destructuring: <code>let { prop1, prop2 } = props.objectProps</code>
You can use the spread operator to do this.
You can simply do <code>&lt;MyJsx {...commonProps} /&gt;</code>
Now what all individual properties you have in commonProps will be sent as individual props to MyJsx.

Is this possible?

Yes its possible, but the way you are sending it is not correct.
The meaning of <code>&lt;MyJsx commonProps /&gt;</code> is:
<code>&lt;MyJsx commonProps={true} /&gt;
</code>
So if you don't specify any value, by default it will take <code>true</code>. To pass the object, you need to write it like this:
<code>const commonProps = {myProp1: 'prop1',myProp2: 'prop2'};
&lt;MyJsx commonProps={commonProps} /&gt;
</code>
Update:
If you have an object and want to pass all the properties as separate prop, write it like this:
<code>&lt;MyJsx {...commonProps} /&gt;
</code>
You can pass props as object in two ways:-
const commonProps = {myProp1: 'prop1',myProp2: 'prop2'};
1.Using spread Operator:-
<code>&lt;MyJsx {...commonProps} /&gt;
</code>
2.Simply pass that props:-
<code>&lt;MyJsx commonProps = {commonProps ? commonProps : true} /&gt;
</code>
